<div class="container">
    <h1>How Databases Work</h1>
    <p>Now that you know what databases are and the different types, let's understand how they actually work behind the scenes in a simple way.</p>

    <h2>1. Storing Data</h2>
    <p>Databases store your data in an organized way so it's easy to find later. For example, if you have a user account, your name, email, and password are stored in a table inside the database.</p>

    <h2>2. Retrieving Data</h2>
    <p>When you log in or request information (like a product list), the application asks the database for that data using a language called <strong>SQL</strong> (Structured Query Language).</p>

    <h2>3. Modifying Data</h2>
    <p>You can add new data (like creating an account), update data (like changing your password), or delete data (like removing a post). These are done with SQL commands like:</p>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Basic SQL Commands</div>
        <div class="code-content">
            <pre><code class="language-sql">
-- Get all users
SELECT * FROM Users;

-- Add a new user
INSERT INTO Users (Name, Email) VALUES ('John', 'john@example.com');

-- Update a user's email
UPDATE Users SET Email = 'new@email.com' WHERE Id = 1;

-- Delete a user
DELETE FROM Users WHERE Id = 1;
            </code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>4. Keeping Things Safe</h2>
    <p>Databases usually have security measures like passwords, user roles, and backups to prevent data loss or unauthorized access.</p>

    <h2>5. Interacting with Applications</h2>
    <p>Most websites and apps use databases to store user data, content, orders, etc. Your application sends requests to the database and receives results — like a conversation.</p>

